This spontaneous report was received from a consumer (grandmother) concerns a Caucasian 13-month-old male 
patient from the United States: 017528281A.
Initial information was processed along with the additional information received on 16-FEB-2016.
The patient's height was not reported and weight was 28 pounds. The patient's medical history was not reported.
The patient was treated with paracetamol (suspension, oral, batch FEB1E00-INV, expiry 30-APR-2017)every 6 
hours, (1 teaspoon every 6 hours-on and off when needed), initiated on 04-FEB-2016 for fever 104 degrees and 
viral infection (bad virus). Concomitant medications were not reported.
On 12-FEB-2016, the patient's grandmother reported that she alternated it with the Children's Tylenol Suspension 
Grape Splash. She stated that she gave him 1 teaspoon every 6 hours, her grandson was running a fever of 104 
and had a bad virus, which was recommended by physician and  physician was aware that she was using it (drug 
prescribed for unapproved indication and off label use).
Laboratory data was provided as follows: body temperature 104. 
The dose of paracetamol was not changed.
The outcome was not reported for drug prescribed for unapproved indication and off label use. 
This report was not serious.
